“I think about it all the time. What have I done wrong this time? Why do they ignore me? Not just at parties, sometimes it happens during the day. I often think something is wrong with me, when in actual fact it was nothing really. In Kazakhstan it is really hard.”

Kazakhstan is one of the trickiest countries of transition this year.

25 years ago, nearly a quarter of its population were migrants and refugees, and life expectancy at birth was 62 years.

While there are signs of progress today, young people like Zhanar worry that people are expecting too much, too quickly.

‘There has to be commitment’
